.TH WITHDRAWAL_PROJECTION 1 "2026-06-23" "finance/planning/annuity" "Annuity Planning Tools"
.SH NAME
withdrawal_projection \- project annuity-equivalent withdrawals from an equity-invested account
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B python withdrawal_projection.py
.I amount age gender state
.RB [ --joint-age
.IR AGE ]
.RB [ --joint-gender
.IR M|F ]
.RB [ --years
.IR N ]
.RB [ --inflation
.IR RATE ]
.RB [ --model
.IR us|global|postwar ]
.RB [ --block-length
.IR YEARS ]
.RB [ --quotes
.IR local|site ]
.RB [ --interest
.IR RATE ]
.RB [ --improvement ]
.RB [ --quote-year
.IR YEAR ]
.RB [ --dynamic-rates ]
.RB [ --initial-rate
.IR RATE ]
.RB [ --upper-bound
.IR FACTOR ]
.RB [ --lower-bound
.IR FACTOR ]
.RB [ --seed
.IR INT ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B withdrawal_projection.py
simulates a single random 30-year path of a retirement strategy that does
.I not
buy an annuity but instead keeps the money invested in equities and each year
withdraws what a life annuity
.I would
pay on the current balance.
.PP
Starting from
.IR amount ,
for each projected year the program:
.IP 1. 4
Prices the monthly life-annuity payout for the current balance at the current
age. By default this uses the local, offline SOA-table pricer
.BR annuity_pricing (1);
.B --quotes site
instead fetches live quotes from
.BR annuity_quote (1)
(immediateannuities.com). Because the payout is linear in the premium, a single
reference rate is computed per age and scaled to the balance.
.IP 2. 4
Withdraws twelve times that monthly payout from the balance, capped at the
balance available (the balance never goes negative; once depleted it stays at
zero and later withdrawals are zero).
.IP 3. 4
Grows the remaining balance by that year's nominal equity return.
.IP 4. 4
Increments the age (and any joint age) by one and repeats.
.PP
Inflation is a single constant rate
.RB ( --inflation ,
default 2.5%), used only to express results in today's dollars. Equity returns
are drawn from the model selected by
.B --model
as historical nominal returns, then
.I restated
onto that constant-inflation basis: each sampled year's embedded historical
inflation is stripped out (preserving its real return) and the constant rate is
applied instead, so the historical inflation once correlated with equity has no
residual effect. Results are reported in nominal dollars (use
.BR montecarlo (1)
for the today's-dollar, inflation-deflated view across many paths).
.PP
The optional
.B --upper-bound
and
.B --lower-bound
factors cap and floor the annual withdrawal in today's dollars, relative to the
first year's withdrawal. For example, if year 1 withdraws the equivalent of
$50,000 in today's dollars, then
.B --upper-bound 1.2
limits every later year to at most $60,000 (today's dollars) and
.B --lower-bound 0.5
keeps every later year at no less than $25,000 (today's dollars). The clamp is
applied to the cash actually withdrawn, so it feeds back into the surviving
balance.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.I amount
Starting amount invested (premium). Accepts plain digits, commas, or a leading
"$" (e.g. \fB1000000\fR, \fB1,000,000\fR, \fB$1,000,000\fR). Must be positive.
.TP
.I age
Age today. Integer 40\(en90 (the quote site's supported entry range; the
projection ages past 90 internally).
.TP
.I gender
\fBM\fR or \fBF\fR (\fBmale\fR/\fBfemale\fR also accepted).
.TP
.I state
Two-letter US state code, e.g. \fBFL\fR, or \fBOTHER\fR. Only used with
\fB--quotes site\fR (the local pricer is state-independent), but always required
on the command line.
.TP
.BI --joint-age " AGE"
Age of a joint (second) beneficiary, 40\(en90. Switches the quote to a joint-life
annuity. Must be given together with \fB--joint-gender\fR.
.TP
.BI --joint-gender " M|F"
Gender of the joint beneficiary. Must be given together with \fB--joint-age\fR.
.TP
.BI --years " N"
Number of years to project. Default \fB30\fR.
.TP
.BI --inflation " RATE"
Constant annual inflation rate as a decimal fraction (e.g. \fB0.025\fR for
2.5%). Used only to deflate results to today's dollars and to restate equity
returns onto a constant-inflation basis. Default \fB0.025\fR.
.TP
.BI --model " us|global|postwar"
Historical return sample, block-bootstrapped (see \fBMODELS\fR).
Default \fBglobal\fR.
.TP
.BI --block-length " YEARS"
Block size in years for the block bootstrap. Default \fB5\fR.
.TP
.BI --quotes " local|site"
Annuity pricing source. \fBlocal\fR (default) prices from the SOA mortality
tables via \fBannuity_pricing\fR(1) \(em fully offline, honouring \fB--interest\fR
and \fB--improvement\fR. \fBsite\fR fetches live immediateannuities.com quotes
(requires network; ignores \fB--interest\fR/\fB--improvement\fR).
.TP
.BI --interest " RATE"
Flat annual interest rate for local pricing, as a decimal fraction. Used only
with \fB--quotes local\fR. Default \fB0.035\fR.
.TP
.B --improvement
Apply SOA Projection Scale G2 mortality improvement (generational projection to
the quote year). Used only with \fB--quotes local\fR; requires the G2 tables
\fBsoa_mortality_2583.csv\fR (male) and \fBsoa_mortality_2584.csv\fR (female).
.TP
.BI --quote-year " YEAR"
Calendar year to project mortality to for \fB--improvement\fR. Default: the
current year.
.TP
.B --dynamic-rates
Use the per-year sampled inflation directly (instead of the constant
\fB--inflation\fR, and with no equity restatement) and evolve the annuity
discount rate with it via the error-correction model in \fBrate_model.py\fR, so a
higher-inflation path produces higher yields and larger nominal payouts. Requires
\fB--model us\fR and \fB--quotes local\fR (the rate model is US-calibrated);
ignores \fB--inflation\fR and \fB--interest\fR. Adds a per-year discount-rate
column to the report.
.TP
.BI --initial-rate " RATE"
Starting ("today's") 10-year rate the dynamic path begins from, as a decimal
fraction. Used only with \fB--dynamic-rates\fR. Default \fB0.043\fR.
.TP
.BI --upper-bound " FACTOR"
Cap the annual withdrawal, in today's dollars, at this factor of the first
year's withdrawal (e.g. \fB1.2\fR). Must be positive. Default: no cap.
.TP
.BI --lower-bound " FACTOR"
Floor the annual withdrawal, in today's dollars, at this factor of the first
year's withdrawal (e.g. \fB0.5\fR). Must be non-negative and not exceed
\fB--upper-bound\fR. Default: no floor.
.TP
.BI --seed " INT"
Seed for the random number generator, for reproducible paths. Default: random.
.SH MODELS
The return sampler is defined in
.BR equity_model.py .
All three choices use the same \fIcircular moving-block bootstrap\fR: consecutive
runs of
.B --block-length
years are resampled and stitched together (wrapping past the end of the series),
which preserves serial correlation \(em notably the year-to-year persistence of
inflation and equity momentum/mean-reversion \(em and so widens the left tail of
multi-year outcomes. Equity and inflation are always drawn as matched pairs.
What differs is \fIwhich history\fR is sampled:
.TP
.B us
The US series alone: paired S&P 500 nominal total return and CPI annual-average
inflation, 1928\(en2025 (see
.BR market_data.py ).
.TP
.B global
A broad sample of developed markets: 16 countries with equity data, 1871\(en2020,
from the Jord\(`a\(enSchularick\(enTaylor Macrohistory Database (see
.BR global_market_data.py ).
Each block is drawn from a single country (countries weighted by their number of
years). The US has been an ex post outlier among developed markets, so this gives
a more cautious, internationally-grounded distribution \(em including
catastrophes the US never saw. Requires the JST data file
.RB ( fetch_global_data.py ).
.TP
.B postwar
The same broad sample restricted to 1950 and later, on the view that the
post-WWII global order is a more relevant guide to the future than the
1870\(en1945 era of world wars and hyperinflations. Sits between \fBus\fR and
\fBglobal\fR.
.SH OUTPUT
A calibration header (model, sample span, equity arithmetic/geometric mean and
standard deviation, CPI mean and standard deviation, equity/inflation
correlation), followed by a year-by-year table: year, age, starting balance,
annual payout (monthly x 12), that year's equity return and inflation, and
ending balance. All dollar figures are nominal. Two summary lines report the
nominal ending balance and the cumulative inflation factor over the projection.
.SH ASSUMPTIONS AND CAVEATS
.IP \(bu 2
This models withdrawing the annuity-\fIequivalent\fR amount while staying
invested in equities. It is \fBnot\fR an annuity purchase: there is no mortality
pooling and no income guarantee, and the balance can be depleted by a poor
sequence of early returns.
.IP \(bu 2
With \fB--quotes local\fR (the default) payouts are priced from the SOA 2012 IAM
mortality tables at a flat \fB--interest\fR rate, with no insurer expense or
profit load; the local pricer handles any age. At the default 3.5% it is
conservative relative to current market quotes (which imply roughly 5%); see
\fBannuity_pricing\fR(1).
.IP \(bu 2
With \fB--quotes site\fR, payouts are "Average Estimated Quotes" scraped live
from immediateannuities.com, not binding rates from a single insurer; network
access is required, and quote ages above 90 are clamped to the age-90 rate (the
site's maximum), which understates the rising payout rate at very old ages.
.IP \(bu 2
A single invocation is one random path. Run with a fixed
.B --seed
for reproducibility; use the Monte Carlo driver for confidence intervals.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
A reproducible single-life projection (local pricing at the default 3.5%):
.PP
.RS
.nf
python withdrawal_projection.py 1000000 65 M FL --seed 1
.fi
.RE
.PP
Local pricing at 4% interest with Scale G2 mortality improvement:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python withdrawal_projection.py 1000000 65 M FL --interest 0.04 --improvement
.fi
.RE
.PP
US sample with dynamic inflation and a discount rate that tracks it:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python withdrawal_projection.py 1000000 65 M FL --model us --dynamic-rates
.fi
.RE
.PP
A joint-life projection on the global sample using live site quotes:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python withdrawal_projection.py 1000000 65 M FL --quotes site \\
    --joint-age 63 --joint-gender F --model global
.fi
.RE
.PP
The post-WWII sample with 10-year blocks to emphasize inflation persistence:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python withdrawal_projection.py 1000000 70 F CA --model postwar --block-length 10
.fi
.RE
.PP
A projection that caps real spending at 120% and floors it at 50% of year 1:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python withdrawal_projection.py 1000000 65 M FL \\
    --upper-bound 1.2 --lower-bound 0.5
.fi
.RE
.SH FILES
.TP
.B withdrawal_projection.py
This program. Exposes \fBbuild_rate_cache()\fR and \fBsimulate_path()\fR for reuse
by a Monte Carlo (many-paths) driver.
.TP
.B annuity_pricing.py
Local SOA-table annuity pricer (the default pricing source).
.TP
.B rate_model.py
Dynamic discount-rate model (error correction on lagged inflation) used by
\fB--dynamic-rates\fR; fitted to FRED GS10 yields and CPI.
.TP
.B soa_mortality_2581.csv, soa_mortality_2582.csv
SOA 2012 IAM base mortality tables (male / female), used by local pricing.
.TP
.B soa_mortality_2583.csv, soa_mortality_2584.csv
SOA Projection Scale G2 improvement tables (male / female), used by
\fB--improvement\fR.
.TP
.B annuity_quote.py
Fetches and parses live site quotes; used only with \fB--quotes site\fR.
.TP
.B equity_model.py
The block-bootstrap equity-return / inflation sampler (us/global/postwar).
.TP
.B market_data.py
Embedded historical US S&P 500 returns and CPI inflation, 1928\(en2025.
.TP
.B global_market_data.py
Broad developed-market returns (JST) for the global/postwar samples; reads the
\fBfetch_global_data.py\fR-derived data file.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
Run with the project virtualenv, which provides NumPy:
.B ~/finance/planning/.venv/bin/python.
The default local pricing runs offline; network access to immediateannuities.com
is required only with \fB--quotes site\fR.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR montecarlo (1),
.BR annuity_pricing (1),
.BR annuity_quote (1)
.SH AUTHOR
Generated for the personal finance planning workspace.
